Responsible Considerations to Select a Model — Detailed Summary

Selecting the right model is one of the most critical steps in building an AI system.

The model you choose affects:

User experience
Product performance
Hiring needs
Deployment speed
Business profitability

AWS tools that help evaluate models:

Amazon Bedrock Model Evaluation
Amazon SageMaker Clarify

These tools help evaluate models based on:

Accuracy
Robustness
Toxicity
Human judgement (quality of responses)
1. Define the Application Use Case Narrowly

One of the most important steps in model selection is clearly defining the specific use case.

A technology is not the same as a use case.

Example:

Technology → Face recognition
Use case → How face recognition is applied.

Example: Traditional AI Use Case

Face recognition can be used for different applications.

Gallery Retrieval

Used to search images of people.

Example: Finding missing persons

Model requirement:

Favor recall

Meaning:
The model should show many possible matches so investigators do not miss someone.

Celebrity Recognition

Used to identify celebrities.

Model requirement:

Favor precision

Meaning:
The model should show only the most accurate match.

Too many results would create confusion.

Virtual Proctoring

Used in online exams.

Model requirement:

Favor precision

Reason:

The system must accurately identify the correct person.

Recall vs Precision Trick

Recall → Find as many possible results as possible

Precision → Find the most accurate result

Memory trick:

Recall = Many results
Precision = Correct results

2. Example: Generative AI Use Case

Example: AI assistant for an online store.

Two possible use cases:

Use Case 1: Product Catalog

Purpose:

Describe products clearly.

Target audience:

Broad audience

Possible issues:

Veracity (truthfulness)

Consequences of errors:

Brand damage
Lost sales
Product returns

Model tuning should focus on:

Neutral tone
Clear descriptions
Complete information
Use Case 2: Persuasion to Buy

Purpose:

Convince customers to purchase.

Target audience:

Narrow demographic

Example:

People living near the coast who may buy boat accessories.

Possible issues:

Veracity problems
Bias
Toxicity
Incorrect details

Consequences:

Brand damage
Sales loss
Customer mistrust
Harm to specific groups

Model tuning should focus on:

Highlighting benefits
Targeted messaging
Addressing specific customer needs
3. Choosing a Model Based on Performance

Model performance depends on multiple factors.

1. Level of Customization

Ability to adjust model behavior.

Levels include:

Prompt engineering
Fine-tuning
Full retraining

Higher customization → better task performance.

2. Model Size

Defined by parameter count.

Large models:

More knowledge
Better reasoning
Higher compute cost

Small models:

Faster
Cheaper
Less capable
3. Inference Options

Ways to deploy the model.

Examples:

Self-managed infrastructure
API calls

Example service:

Amazon Bedrock
4. Licensing Agreements

Some models have restrictions such as:

Non-commercial use only
Limited redistribution
Attribution requirements

Always check license terms.

5. Context Window

Context window = amount of text the model can process in one prompt.

Example:

Large context window allows:

Long documents
Complex conversations
Code analysis

Small context window limits prompt size.

6. Latency

Latency = time required to generate a response

Low latency:

Faster user experience
Better real-time applications

High latency:

Slower interactions

Example use cases needing low latency:

Chatbots
Customer service assistants
4. Evaluate Models Using Test Datasets

A common mistake is thinking:

“Model A is better than Model B.”

In reality:

Performance = Model + Dataset

A model may perform differently depending on the dataset.

Example:

Model performs well on Dataset A
Performs better on Dataset B
Performs poorly on Dataset C

This means both model development and dataset development must be considered.

Datasets are not static.

They change over time.

So evaluation must be continuous.

5. Sustainability Considerations

Responsible AI must consider long-term sustainability.

Sustainability includes:

Social impact
Environmental impact
Economic impact
6. Responsible Agency

Responsible agency means AI systems should make ethical and socially responsible decisions.

Key components include:

Value Alignment

AI should follow human values and ethics.

Example:

Avoid harmful outputs
Respect fairness
Responsible Reasoning Skills

AI should make logical and ethical decisions.

Example:

Avoid generating misinformation.

Appropriate Level of Autonomy

AI should only have the right amount of independence.

Example:

Critical decisions may require human approval.

Transparency and Accountability

AI systems should be explainable.

Users should know:

How decisions are made
Who is responsible
7. Environmental Considerations

AI systems consume large amounts of computing resources.

Responsible AI considers environmental impact.

Key concerns:

Energy Consumption

Large models require:

Data centers
GPUs
Electricity

Solution:

Use efficient models when possible.

Resource Utilization

AI uses resources such as:

Hardware
Cloud infrastructure
Storage

Efficient resource use reduces costs and environmental impact.

Environmental Impact Assessment

Organizations should evaluate:

Carbon footprint
Energy usage
Sustainability of infrastructure
8. Economic Considerations

AI technologies can impact the economy.

Positive impacts:

Automation
Increased productivity
Cost savings

Negative impacts:

Job displacement
Income inequality
Concentration of power in large tech companies

Example concern:

Large companies controlling:

AI models
Data
Cloud infrastructure

This could create monopolies.

Responsible AI must balance innovation with fairness.
